03392nam a22004455i 9780773563957DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19931993xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735639577 a10.1515/97807735639572doi  a(DE-B1597)657113  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aLC375bT48 1993eb 7aFOR0300002bisacsh04a268/.011 aThiessen, Elmer John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTeaching for Commitment :bLiberal Education, Indoctrination, and Christian Nurture /cElmer John Thiessen. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1993] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tThe Charge of Religious Indoctrination -- tLiberal Education: The Context of the Charge of Indoctrination -- tContent of Indoctrination and the Scientific Ideal -- tMethods of Indoctrination and the Ideal of Rationality -- tIntentions of the Indoctrinator and the Ideal of Autonomy -- tConsequences of Indoctrination and the Ideal of Critical Openness -- tInstitutional Indoctrination and the Democratic Ideal of Liberal Institutions -- tReligious Indoctrination vs Liberal Education: Some Conclusions -- tSome Practical Suggestions -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThiessen calls for reconstruction of the Enlightenment ideal of liberal education from which the charge of indoctrination typically arises. He argues that liberal education necessarily builds on nurture and therefore needs to be more sensitive to the traditions into which a child is initiated. The ideals of autonomy, rationality, and critical openness - all closely related to the ideal of liberal education - need to be modified if they are to be both realistic and philosophically defensible. Once this is done it can be seen that confessional religious education without indoctrination is possible. Teaching for Commitment is an interdisciplinary study covering the fields of religion, philosophy, epistemology, ethics, and education. The very practical nature of the problem being examined, and Thiessen's straightforward and non-technical presentation, will be of interest to parochial and public school boards, teachers, and parents, as well as religious institutions, educationalists, and philosophers of education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Indic Languages.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356395740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773563957423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773563957/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles